e most slowly rotating\nstars of each spectral subtype have the strongest H$\\alpha$ absorption.\nH$\\alpha$ is correlated most strongly with He I D3, whereas Na I D and the Ca\nII infrared triplet are also correlated with H$\\alpha$. He I $\\lambda$10833\n{\\AA} and Pa$\\beta$ show no clear correlations with the other indicators. The\nTiO bands show an activity effect that does not appear in the VO bands. We find\nthat the relative variations of H$\\alpha$ and He I D3 are smaller for stars\nwith higher activity levels, while this anti-correlation is weaker for Na I D\nand the Ca II infrared triplet, and is absent for He I $\\lambda$10833 {\\AA} and\nPa$\\beta$. Periodic variation with the rotation period most commonly appears in\nthe TiO bands, H$\\alpha$, and in the Ca II infrared triplet.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 25 Jan 2019 13:00:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-06"}
